{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569056"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:24:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:24:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21706"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21706"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.03,0.04,0.02,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14575"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104903"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14575"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21706"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87289"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"3619"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"36851"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36852"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45783"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104903"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. During the physical examination, the doctor notices a small, bright red, dome-shaped papule under the patient\u0027s left eye (Image). The patient reports it has been present for many months without change and does not cause any symptoms. No other similar lesions are found elsewhere on his body. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Basal cell carcinoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Pinguecula","Hordeolum","Cherry angioma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image shows a small, bright red, dome-shaped papule that is characteristic of a cherry angioma. \u003Cstrong\u003ECherry angiomas\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as Campbell de Morgan spots) are benign vascular proliferations composed of dilated capillaries. They typically appear as bright red, dome-shaped papules ranging from 1-5 mm in diameter. They are common in adults over 30 years of age and tend to increase in number with advancing age. They can appear anywhere on the body but are most common on the trunk and proximal extremities. The lesion\u0027s stable nature over months and asymptomatic presentation are consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E (BCC) typically presents as a pearly or waxy papule with telangiectasias, often with central ulceration or a rolled border. BCCs grow slowly over months to years and may bleed easily. They are most common in sun-exposed areas such as the face. The bright red appearance and dome shape in this case are not typical features of a BCC.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E (SCC) usually presents as a firm, red, scaly or crusted plaque or nodule that may ulcerate. SCCs often arise from actinic keratoses in sun-damaged skin. The smooth, dome-shaped appearance without scaling or ulceration makes SCC unlikely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPinguecula\u003C/strong\u003E is a yellowish, slightly raised conjunctival lesion that typically occurs on the nasal or temporal side of the cornea. It represents a degenerative change of the conjunctival tissue with elastoid deposition. The bright red color and location under the eye rather than on the conjunctiva make pinguecula an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHordeolum\u003C/strong\u003E (stye) is an acute infection of the eyelid margin, usually involving an eyelash follicle or meibomian gland. It presents as a painful, erythematous, swollen area on the eyelid that may point and discharge pus. The chronic, asymptomatic nature of this lesion and its location under the eye rather than on the eyelid margin are inconsistent with a hordeolum.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003ECherry angiomas are benign and typically require no treatment unless they bleed, cause discomfort, or there are cosmetic concerns. If treatment is desired, options include electrocautery, shave excision, or laser therapy. The patient should be reassured about the benign nature of the lesion and advised to monitor for any changes in size, color, or symptoms that might warrant reassessment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cherry angiomas are benign vascular proliferations that appear as small, bright red papules on the skin.","Cherry angiomas are common in adults over 30 years of age and increase in number with advancing age.","Cherry angiomas require no treatment unless they bleed, cause discomfort, or there are cosmetic concerns."],"references":["Vilas Boas P, Cerroni L, Requena L. Intravascular Cutaneous Disorders. A Clinicopathologic Review. Am J Dermatopathol 2021; 43:119\u201336. Available from: https://journals.lww.com/amjdermatopathology/fulltext/2021/02000/intravascular_cutaneous_disorders__a.5.aspx","Clarke P. Benign pigmented skin lesions. Aust J Gen Pract. 2019 Jun;48(6):364\u20137. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2019/june/benign-pigmented-skin-lesions"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87289"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21706"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21913"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21913","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21913"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fGGDw53sZZovcSYARAf3gn5Sw0KbAB.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fGGDw53sZZovcSYARAf3gn5Sw0KbAB.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87289"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-05T17:02:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-05T17:07:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14575"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104903"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"po